all, England, United Kingdom":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Anglie, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1313–ABT 1363":"omkring 1313–omkring 1363","1313–1363":"1313–1363","1316–1416":"1316–1416","1342–1385":"1342–1385","1283–1344":"1283–1344","1302–1313":"1302–1313","1316":"1316","1313":"1313","1302":"1302","ABT 1363":"omkring 1363","1344":"1344","1342":"1342","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","about 1313":"omkring 1313","about 1335":"omkring 1335","1283":"1283","1416":"1416","Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England"},"nl":{"about 1313–ABT 1363":"circa 1313–circa 1363","1313–1363":"1313–1363","1316–1416":"1316–1416","1342–1385":"1342–1385","1283–1344":"1283–1344","1302–1313":"1302–1313","1316":"1316","1313":"1313","1302":"1302","ABT 1363":"circa 1363","1344":"1344","1342":"1342","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","about 1313":"circa 1313","about 1335":"circa 1335","1283":"1283","1416":"1416","Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"about 1313–ABT 1363":"about 1313–about 1363","1313–1363":"1313–1363","1316–1416":"1316–1416","1342–1385":"1342–1385","1283–1344":"1283–1344","1302–1313":"1302–1313","1316":"1316","1313":"1313","1302":"1302","ABT 1363":"about 1363","1344":"1344","1342":"1342","1385":"1385","1363":"1363","about 1313":"about 1313","about 1335":"about 1335","1283":"1283","1416":"1416","Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Petit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Michel, Normand, Mireille, Philippe, Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Pattee","meanings":["Altered form of French (Nord) <b>Pety</b>: variant of   Petit  . This surname was brought to North America from England."]},{"name":"Petion","meanings":["French and Haitian (<b>Pétion</b>): diminutive of   Petit  . This surname was brought to the US from Haiti, where it is by far most common."]},{"name":"Petite","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Petitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Pettett","meanings":["English: variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Little","meanings":["English: nickname for a small man (if not ironic), or distinguishing epithet for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, from Middle English <i>littel</i>, Old English <i>lȳtel</i> (see   Light   3).","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Beagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beagán</i>’ (see   Began  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of any of various European surnames meaning ‘little’, e.g. French   Petit  , Polish <b>Mały</b> (see   Maly   1)."]},{"name":"Petee","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Pettie","meanings":["Pet form derived from various girls' names ending in the syllable <i>-nette</i>, for example   Annette   and   Jeannette  , with the diminutive suffix <i>-ie</i>. It had a brief vogue in the late 19th and early 20th centuries."]},{"name":"Pettit","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."]},{"name":"Petito","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasquale, Antonio, Rocco, Alfonzo, Alphonso, Antimo, Emilio, Giovanni, Giuseppe, Orazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Tullio, Virginio.","Italian: nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a tall one), from dialect <i>petito</i> ‘small’ or from the personal name <i>Petito</i>; compare French   Petit  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Petit Lord of Trenerth was born about 1313, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Petit, was 31 and his mother, Isabella Monfort Heligan, was 12. He married Johanna Carminow about 1335. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1363, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1313–ABT 1363":"umbes 1313–umbes 1363","1313–1363":"1313–1363","1316–1416":"1316–1416","1342–1385":"1342